## 6. Contestant's `on_tick()` Experience (Clean OOP)

```python
def on_tick(state, orders):
    # ── Live Market State (bots have already responded to your last trade) ──
    state.bid_price           # best bid right now
    state.ask_price           # best ask
    state.spread              # widens after you take too much liquidity
    state.bid_depth           # [vol@best, vol@best-1, ..., @best-4]
    state.ask_depth           # same on ask side
    state.last_trade_price
    state.underlying_signal   # reference fair value (from platform)

    # ── Your State ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    state.position            # net position
    state.cash
    state.pnl                 # mark-to-market
    state.open_orders         # your resting limit orders in LOB

    # ── Fill Notifications (from PREVIOUS tick's orders) ────────────────
    for fill in state.fills:
        fill.price; fill.volume; fill.side  # 'buy' or 'sell'

    # ── Your Persistent State (0ns IPC, lives across ticks) ─────────────
    state.ema_fast; state.tick_count  # ... + 14 more int64 slots

    # ── Order Submission (max 4 per tick) ────────────────────────────────
    orders.limit_buy(price=1500.20, volume=10)
    orders.limit_sell(price=1500.40, volume=5)
    orders.market_buy(volume=20)
    orders.market_sell(volume=20)
    orders.cancel(order_id=state.open_orders[0].id)
```

